{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":3,"markdown":"At the national level, data completeness is very high, with most indicators consistently above 95%.

However, two indicators — maternal deaths and still births — have much lower completeness (~31-32%), which may affect reliability for those services. New family planning acceptors and postnatal visit within 48 hours of delivery have moderate completeness (~87-90%).

Completeness also varies by province, as Copperbelt, Lusaka, and Northwestern have average completeness below 89%."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":0.7,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"c20f1672-edfc-4140-ae2c-09a30b50443a","moduleId":"m001","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":true}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Reporting completeness"}}

