{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"image","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"imgFile":"Zambia_vid-nurse-checkup_FASTR.jpg","imgFit":"cover","markdown":"","imgStretch":true,"imgHeight":250},{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"primary","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"markdown":"The FASTR approach uses routine HMIS data to monitor how service delivery shifts over time.

By comparing observed vs. expected service volumes — adjusted for seasonality and historical trends — we can identify disruptions or surpluses in key health services.

This analysis provides a timely, system-wide perspective, highlighting where and when service use deviates from expected patterns. Findings generate actionable evidence to guide rapid responses, helping sustain continuity of essential care during funding uncertainty or operational change."}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Tracking Disruptions in Essential Services Using HMIS Data","useFooter":false,"footerLogos":[]}}

